## DataBase
## What is a database?
A database is best described as a collection of information and data that is often stored in tables,
columns and rows. Databases are frequently stored on a server which can be queried for data
management. Create, read, update and delete (CRUD) operations are common uses for relational
databases.


## Importance of databases
-> Enables organisations to manage and store important data.
-> Provides organisations with meaningful insight.
-> Allows organisations to formulate enhanced business strategy.
-> Enhances the efficiency of existing organisational processes.


Types of common databases
1. Relational database 
->Adopts the relational model in that rows, fields, tables and columns are
related to one another by using constraints such as primary and foreign keys. Relational
databases are often used to manage structured data.

2. NoSQL database 
–> Frequently used to manage unstructured data. Unlike relational databases
where there tends to be some apparent order and structure, a NoSQL database stores data in
files, documents and collections instead of tables.


3. Cloud database 
–> These types of databases can be either structured or unstructured, the
distinguishing characteristic is that this type of database is accessible via the cloud and is hosted by third-party services.

